mbuzz uses **AML (Attribution Model Language)** to configure attribution models. AML is a simple, declarative syntax that lets you define exactly how credit should be distributed.

### Basic Linear Model

```yaml
# mbuzz AML - Linear Attribution
model: linear
name: "Equal Credit"
description: "Distribute credit equally across all touchpoints"

settings:
  lookback_window: 30d
  include_direct: true
  dedupe_level: session    # session | event
  min_touchpoints: 1
```

This creates a standard linear model with 30-day lookback, including direct traffic, deduplicating at the session level.

### Linear with Channel Filtering

```yaml
# Only credit marketing channels (exclude direct/organic brand)
model: linear
name: "Marketing Linear"

settings:
  lookback_window: 30d

filters:
  exclude_channels:
    - direct
    - organic_brand
  include_only:
    - paid_social
    - paid_search
    - email
    - display
    - affiliate
```

### Running Multiple Linear Models

```yaml
# Compare different lookback windows
models:
  - model: linear
    name: "Linear 7d"
    settings:
      lookback_window: 7d

  - model: linear
    name: "Linear 30d"
    settings:
      lookback_window: 30d

  - model: linear
    name: "Linear 90d"
    settings:
      lookback_window: 90d

comparison:
  enabled: true
  primary: "Linear 30d"
```

## Tuning Linear Parameters for Your Business

Linear attribution has few parameters, but the ones it has matter. Here's how to tune them for different contexts.

### By Business Type

| Business Type | Lookback Window | Include Direct? | Dedupe Level |
|---------------|-----------------|-----------------|--------------|
| **Impulse e-commerce** | 7 days | Yes | Session |
| **Considered purchase** | 30 days | Yes | Session |
| **B2B SaaS** | 60-90 days | No (often brand) | Session |
| **Enterprise B2B** | 90-180 days | No | Event (capture all) |
| **Subscription/DTC** | 30 days | Yes | Session |

### By Business Stage

```yaml
# Early-stage: Simple, learn your baseline
model: linear
name: "Startup Linear"
settings:
  lookback_window: 30d
  include_direct: true
  dedupe_level: session

---

# Growth-stage: More nuance, exclude noise
model: linear
name: "Growth Linear"
settings:
  lookback_window: 30d
  include_direct: false    # Brand strength distorts

filters:
  exclude_channels:
    - organic_brand        # Exclude branded organic
  min_conversion_value: 10 # Ignore micro-conversions

---

# Scale-stage: Segment analysis
models:
  - model: linear
    name: "New Customer Linear"
    settings:
      lookback_window: 60d
    filters:
      user_segment: new_customers

  - model: linear
    name: "Returning Linear"
    settings:
      lookback_window: 14d    # Shorter for returning
    filters:
      user_segment: returning_customers
```

### Seasonal Adjustments

During major campaigns or seasonal peaks, journey patterns change:

```yaml
# Black Friday / Holiday Season
model: linear
name: "Holiday Linear"
settings:
  lookback_window: 14d      # Compressed buying cycles
  include_direct: true

date_range:
  start: "2024-11-15"
  end: "2024-12-31"

# Compare to baseline
comparison:
  baseline_model: "Standard Linear"
  baseline_period: "2024-10-01 to 2024-11-14"
```

### Big Campaign / Launch Adjustments

When launching a major campaign, isolate its attribution:

```yaml
# Product Launch Attribution
model: linear
name: "Launch Linear"

settings:
  lookback_window: 14d      # Fresh launch, short history

filters:
  # Only attribute conversions where launch campaign was touched
  require_campaign:
    - "product-launch-2024"
    - "launch-retargeting"

# Track daily to see ramp
reporting:
  granularity: daily
  compare_to_forecast: true
```

### Parameter Tuning Cheatsheet

| Scenario | Parameter Change | Why |
|----------|------------------|-----|
| **Faster sales cycle** | Shorter lookback (7-14d) | Avoid crediting irrelevant old touches |
| **Slower sales cycle** | Longer lookback (60-90d) | Capture full journey |
| **Strong brand** | Exclude direct | Brand visits distort marketing credit |
| **New market/product** | Include direct | Every touch matters, brand is weak |
| **High-frequency touchpoints** | Session dedupe | Avoid over-crediting email opens etc. |
| **Low-frequency, high-value touches** | Event dedupe | Capture every interaction |
| **Seasonality spike** | Shorter lookback | Reflect compressed cycles |
| **Post-holiday normalization** | Longer lookback | Account for gift card redemptions |

## Summary

Linear attribution distributes credit equally across all touchpoints. It's simple, transparent, and unbiased—making it the ideal baseline for multi-touch attribution.

**Use linear when:**
- Moving from single-touch to multi-touch attribution
- You want a neutral, unbiased view of contribution
- Journey touchpoints are roughly equal in importance
- You need a baseline to compare other models against

**Don't rely solely on linear because:**
- Some touchpoints genuinely matter more than others
- It may dilute credit across low-impact touches
- It doesn't capture recency or position effects

**Best practice:** Start with linear, understand your baseline, then explore time-decay or position-based if you have strong hypotheses about touchpoint importance. Validate any model with incrementality tests.

